"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezekiel-1-5.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ezekiel.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ezekiel.json
- data/translation/notes/ezekiel.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch1 merkabah vision: ANE composite-creature background (Assyrian lamassu/Babylonian shedu)
  treated as polemic context rather than borrowing — YHWH's chariot throne refutes Babylonian territorial theology
- Ch3 watchman theology: four-case blood-guilt matrix read as a formal theological structure, not a
  legal code; precedents in ANE sentinel/sentinel-liability practices
- Ch4 sign-acts: day-for-year principle and 390+40 day calculation treated as typological number
  without committing to a single historical resolution scheme
- Ch5 central-nations claim: cosmographical claim read in light of ANE world-map traditions (Babylonian
  mappa mundi), not as literal cartography
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "2": "<p>The parenthetical date-note (v. 2-3) anchors the vision historically: the fifth year of Jehoiachin's exile = 593 BCE. Jehoiachin (Jeconiah) had been deported with the second wave in 597 BCE (2 Kings 24:10-16) along with 10,000 skilled workers and warriors. He remained a recognized king in Babylonian records — the Weidner Tablets (discovered in Babylon) list rations issued to 'Yaukin, king of Judah' and his sons, confirming his quasi-royal status in exile. The Babylonian exile was not a prison but an administrative relocation; deportees like Ezekiel could own property, build houses, and conduct business (as Jer 29:4-7 counsels). This context matters: Ezekiel's audience was not enslaved and desperate but economically active and tempted to assimilate.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Ezekiel's dual identity as priest and prophet (<em>kohen</em> and <em>navi</em>) is unusual — only Jeremiah shares this combination among the writing prophets. His priestly formation shaped everything: the book's obsession with the temple, the divine glory (<em>kavod</em>), holiness distinctions, and the liturgical calendar. The <strong>River Chebar</strong> (Hebrew <em>nahar K'bar</em>) has been identified with the <em>nar Kabari</em> in Babylonian administrative texts — a canal near Nippur in southern Mesopotamia where a Jewish deportee community is attested. The phrase &#8220;the hand of the LORD was upon him&#8221; (<em>yad YHWH aleiv</em>) is Ezekiel's characteristic marker for the onset of the ecstatic visionary state (also 3:14, 22; 8:1; 33:22; 37:1; 40:1); it is closely paralleled in Elijah (1 Kings 18:46) and Elisha (2 Kings 3:15) but appears more frequently in Ezekiel than in any other prophet.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theophanic approach from the north is charged with polemical significance. In Canaanite mythology, Baal's divine mountain (<em>Zaphon</em>) was located to the north — Psalm 48:2 appropriates this tradition by identifying Zion with &#8220;the heights of Zaphon.&#8221; Storm-theophanies from the north signal divine approach in the warrior-god tradition. Crucially, Ezekiel is in Babylon when the northward storm arrives — implying that YHWH is not geographically confined to Jerusalem or Canaan. This directly refutes the Babylonian theological assumption that deporting a people means defeating their god: YHWH's throne-chariot is mobile and present in exile. The &#8220;gleaming metal&#8221; (<em>hashmal</em>) in the fire-center is a hapax legomenon whose precise meaning is unknown — possibly electrum (gold-silver alloy) or a supernatural luminescent substance. The LXX translates it <em>elektron</em>; later rabbinic tradition treated it as a divine energy so dangerous that unauthorized exposition of the merkabah chapter required the teacher to be surrounded by fire.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The four living creatures (<em>hayyot</em>, literally &#8220;living ones&#8221;) are identified as cherubim (<em>keruvim</em>) in ch. 10 — not the soft-winged infant figures of later Christian art but the fierce guardian-beings of the ANE. Composite figures with multiple faces appear throughout ancient Near Eastern royal iconography: Assyrian <em>lamassu</em> (winged human-headed bulls protecting palace entrances), Babylonian <em>apkallu</em> (fish-sages with divine wisdom), Egyptian sphinxes. Ezekiel's hayyot are recognizably within this tradition but transformed: they serve YHWH's throne, not a pagan king's palace. The original audience in Babylon, surrounded by these monumental composite figures on every temple gateway, would have understood the visual claim immediately — YHWH's attendants are superior to Babylon's guardian figures.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Four faces and four wings are specified here (cf. Isaiah's seraphim who have six wings, Isa 6:2; Revelation's living creatures also have six wings, Rev 4:8 — suggesting Ezekiel's count differs from the heavenly court in other visions). The number four in ANE cosmography represents the four cardinal directions and hence universality — the four-faced, four-winged creatures embody YHWH's omnidirectional sovereignty, not limited to any single spatial orientation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;Straight legs&#8221; (possibly meaning unbent, single-joint) and &#8220;a calf's hoof&#8221; — bovine feet signal the ox-face component of the composite being. The gleaming bronze (<em>nechoshet qalal</em>, burnished bronze) evokes the bronze sea and bronze pillars of Solomon's temple (1 Kings 7:15-16, 23-26). Priestly temple-knowledge would make these associations immediate for Ezekiel: the hayyot carry the vocabulary of the temple into Babylonian exile, asserting continuity between YHWH's earthly dwelling and his heavenly throne.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Human hands beneath their wings represent capacity for purposeful action — distinguishing these beings from mere natural forces. The fourfold symmetry (each face on each side) emphasizes the uniformity and order of YHWH's heavenly court. The absence of asymmetry or imperfection is a theological statement: no chaos, no conflict within the divine retinue — in stark contrast to the conflict-laden Babylonian creation myth (Enuma Elish) where the divine order is achieved through violence and disorder.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The wings touching neighbors and straight-ahead movement without turning expresses the absolute purposefulness of the divine chariot's movement. In ANE military contexts, disciplined marching without turning was a mark of elite troops. Here it expresses that YHWH's purposes are not diverted or deflected by external obstacles — the divine chariot moves where the Spirit directs, without the hesitation or recalibration that characterizes human planning.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The four faces — human, lion, ox, eagle — have generated extensive interpretation. Irenaeus (2nd century CE) was the first to map them onto the four Gospels (Matthew/human, Mark/lion, Luke/ox, John/eagle), a scheme that became standard in Christian iconography (the symbols of the four Evangelists). In Ezekiel's context, these represent the four dominant animal categories: the most intelligent creature (human), king of wild beasts (lion), king of domestic animals (ox), king of birds (eagle) — together suggesting the totality of the animate creation in service of YHWH's throne. The Babylonian deities had their own animal emblems and were often depicted in composite form; Ezekiel's vision appropriates and transcends this visual vocabulary.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The wing-configuration — two spread outward touching neighbors, two covering the body — creates both connection (to the neighboring hayyot) and modesty (covering their own form before the divine presence). The same instinct of covering before YHWH appears in Isaiah's seraphim (Isa 6:2: two wings to cover the face, two to cover the feet). Even the highest heavenly beings are not fully unveiled before the divine glory — a consistent theme that relativizes all created beings before YHWH.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;Each moved straight ahead — wherever the spirit directed them.&#8221; The Hebrew <em>ruach</em> here is probably the divine Spirit rather than simply &#8220;wind&#8221; — the beings move as the Spirit moves within them. This is consistent with ancient Near Eastern divine-throne theology: the king's divine attendants execute his will with perfect responsiveness. But Ezekiel's point is that the Spirit of YHWH (not the spirits of Babylonian deities) animates the cosmic order.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Burning coals and blazing torches moving among the hayyot evoke the theophanic fire of Sinai (Exod 19:18) and the pillar of fire in the wilderness (Exod 13:21). Fire is YHWH's signature element in theophany — it is the medium through which the divine presence manifests while remaining unapproachable (Heb 12:29: &#8220;our God is a consuming fire,&#8221; citing Deut 4:24). Lightning (<em>baraq</em>) flashing from the fire intensifies the storm-theophany motif of v. 4.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The darting movement like a lightning flash completes the storm-theophany: wind (v. 4), cloud (v. 4), fire (v. 4, 13), lightning (v. 13, 14). All four classical theophanic elements are present. In Canaanite religion these were Baal's storm attributes; Psalm 29 already repurposed this storm-god imagery for YHWH. Ezekiel does the same but in the context of Babylonian exile, where Marduk (the Babylonian storm-creator deity) is the dominant religious claim. YHWH's throne-chariot arrives in Babylon with all the attributes of divine cosmic sovereignty.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The <em>ophanim</em> (wheels) appear beside each of the four hayyot when they land. The wheel-within-wheel design (v. 16) has been compared to gyroscopic mechanisms and astronomical models; the most plausible ancient parallel is the Babylonian astronomical tradition of wheels representing planetary motion. Babylonian astral religion had developed sophisticated mathematical astronomy by the 6th century BCE — the stars and planets were divine beings whose movements determined fate. Ezekiel's vision places a YHWH-controlled mechanism above all this astral machinery: the ophanim are not cosmic fate-wheels but YHWH's chariot-wheels, responsive to the Spirit, not to astrological determinism.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;Like beryl&#8221; (<em>tarshish</em>) — probably a yellow or golden gemstone; Tarshish-stone appears also in Dan 10:6. The description &#8220;a wheel intersecting a wheel&#8221; (<em>ophan betokh haophan</em>) allows omnidirectional movement without turning — a mechanical impossibility in human engineering, serving as a visual marker of the supernatural. The wheels' ability to move in any of the four directions without turning reinforces the omnidirectional sovereignty expressed by the four faces.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The capacity to move in any direction without turning was functionally important for ancient military formations (turning a unit exposes flanks). Here it expresses perfect divine freedom of movement — YHWH is not constrained by the geography that constrains human armies. The Babylonian theology that a defeated nation's god could not function outside its territorial homeland is directly refuted: YHWH's throne is mobile and omnidirectionally operative.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The &#8220;rims full of eyes&#8221; is one of the most striking features of the vision and appears again in Rev 4:6. In ANE iconography, multiple eyes on divine beings symbolize omniscience — the ability to see in all directions simultaneously. The Babylonian deity Marduk was described as &#8220;four-eyed,&#8221; and the sun-god Shamash (god of justice and judgment) was depicted with eyes everywhere. Ezekiel's ophanim with eye-covered rims claim YHWH's total omniscient surveillance — appropriate for a God whose throne-chariot is present in the land of the enemy.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The perfect coordination between hayyot and ophanim — rising together, moving together — establishes the unity of the divine vehicle. Unlike the Babylonian divine assembly where multiple deities have potentially competing agendas, YHWH's heavenly court operates in perfect unity. The exilic community, watching Babylon's elaborate divine processions (the New Year festival featured the barges of multiple deities processing through the city), would recognize what Ezekiel was countering: YHWH's heavenly host is more coherent and more powerful than Babylon's divine bureaucracy.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;The spirit of the living creature was in the wheels&#8221; (<em>ruach hahayyah baophanim</em>) — the Spirit animates both the living creatures and the wheels as a single unified system. This is not mechanism but life: the divine chariot is a living entity, not a machine. The Babylonian astronomical system was deterministic — planetary movements were calculable fate-machinery. Ezekiel insists YHWH's cosmic governance is personal, Spirit-animated, and responsive to the divine will rather than mechanical and predetermined.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The repetition of the coordination formula (vv. 19-21) is characteristic of Ezekiel's style: he describes the same feature multiple times from slightly different angles. Scholars have proposed various explanations (scribal additions, literary ring-structure, liturgical repetition). The most likely function is emphatic: the perfect responsiveness of the divine chariot to the divine will is so important theologically that it bears repetition. The exilic community needed to know that YHWH's movements were not random or uncontrolled.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The <em>raqia</em> (firmament) stretched above the hayyot echoes Genesis 1:6-8, where the raqia separates the waters above from below. Ezekiel's firmament is &#8220;like crystal&#8221; (<em>keein haqqarach hanoorah</em> — like the awesome ice/crystal) and hovers between the hayyot and the divine throne. The cosmological structure mirrors the priestly cosmology: below (earth/exile), the hayyot-level (heavenly court), the firmament (boundary of the divine realm), the throne (YHWH's presence). This vertical structure places YHWH definitively above the Babylonian cosmos.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Wings spread straight out, two covering the body — the modesty gesture before the divine presence reappears. The precise description of wing-angles in liturgical context suggests priestly vocabulary: the placement and orientation of priestly garments, the arrangement of temple objects, the position of the cherubim in the Holy of Holies (Exod 25:20) were all regulated with this level of precision. Ezekiel is describing a heavenly temple whose furnishings correspond to and surpass the earthly one.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;Like the sound of many waters, like the voice of the Almighty&#8221; (<em>kekol mayim rabbim kekol Shaddai</em>) — both phrases are theophanic comparisons. &#8220;Many waters&#8221; (<em>mayim rabbim</em>) is the OT's characteristic sound for YHWH's voice (Ps 29:3; Rev 1:15; 14:2). <em>Shaddai</em> (the Almighty) is an ancient divine name associated particularly with the patriarchal period and the book of Job, where it occurs 31 times. Its sound-comparison here suggests the deep resonance of overwhelming power rather than words. The &#8220;great rumbling like the noise of an army&#8221; frames YHWH as divine warrior — a title directly applicable to the Babylonian military context of exile.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The lowering of wings when the hayyot stand still corresponds to the silence that falls when YHWH speaks from above the firmament. This is theophanic liturgy: when the voice is about to speak, all subsidiary sounds cease. The same pattern appears at Mount Sinai where the people fell silent before the divine voice (Exod 20:18-19). The vision is structured as a heavenly liturgical assembly that mirrors and exceeds the earthly cult — a crucial assertion for a community whose earthly temple is inaccessible.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;Something like a sapphire throne&#8221; (<em>keein aven sapir demut kisse</em>) — sapphire (or lapis lazuli) is the characteristic throne-material in ANE divine-council literature. The Sinai elders &#8220;saw the God of Israel, and under his feet was something like a pavement of sapphire&#8221; (Exod 24:10). In Mesopotamian literature, lapis lazuli was the material of the heavens themselves — its deep blue represented the sky's vault. Ezekiel's sapphire throne places YHWH above the very heaven that Babylon identified with the divine realm. &#8220;A form with a human appearance&#8221; (<em>demut kemar-eh adam</em>) above the throne is the most theologically careful part of the vision: not Adam, not an angel, not a named deity — a form that resembles a human figure. This reserve is specifically anti-idolatrous.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The description from waist up/waist down in fire and radiance recalls the fire-within-fire of v. 4 but now personalized. The entire vision has been building to this: the fire-storm from the north, the hayyot, the wheels, the firmament — all are the entourage and vehicle of this figure. The refusal to describe the figure more precisely is itself theologically significant: Deuteronomy's prohibition of images (Deut 4:15-18) was based precisely on the fact that Israel saw no form (temunah) at Sinai. Ezekiel sees a form but describes it only through negation and approximation — a visionary language that preserves the Deuteronomic reserve while asserting genuine divine presence.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The rainbow surrounding the divine glory recalls the covenant sign of Genesis 9:13-16 — the first time YHWH appeared in glory surrounded by a rainbow was after the flood, as a covenant promise. Ezekiel sees the rainbow in Babylon: the covenant faithfulness that YHWH displayed to Noah is present even in the place of exile and judgment. This is the hope embedded in the terrifying vision: the God who appears in storm and fire is also the God of the covenant rainbow. The prophet falls on his face — the standard prostration response to divine theophany (cf. Isa 6:5; Dan 8:17; Rev 1:17) — and hears a voice, which initiates the commission of ch. 2.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>&#8220;Son of man, stand on your feet&#8221; (<em>ben-adam, amad al-ragleykha</em>) — the command to rise after prostration is the standard commissioning gesture in prophetic and angelic encounter literature. Moses hid his face at the burning bush (Exod 3:6); Isaiah was undone by the vision (Isa 6:5); Daniel fell prostrate at every heavenly encounter. The divine command to stand signals that the encounter is purposive — not for contemplation but for commission. <em>Ben-adam</em> (son of man) is Ezekiel's characteristic address, occurring 93 times in the book — more than in the entire rest of the OT combined. It simultaneously emphasizes human creaturely finitude (as opposed to the divine glory just witnessed) and authorizes the prophet as YHWH's representative.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Spirit entering the prophet to enable him to stand (<em>vatavo bi ruach vaatamideni al-raglai</em>) is the pneumatological dimension of prophetic commissioning. In OT theology the Spirit comes upon prophets to empower speech and action (1 Sam 10:6; Isa 61:1; Joel 2:28). Here the Spirit's first action is more basic: to enable the prophet to stand upright before the divine presence. The Spirit's empowerment for prophetic mission begins with the most elemental act — standing — before proceeding to speaking.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;To nations that have rebelled against me&#8221; — the unusual plural &#8220;nations&#8221; (<em>goyim</em>) for Israel/Judah suggests that Israel's covenant-breach has made them functionally indistinguishable from the pagan nations in terms of their rebellious relationship to YHWH. The same rhetorical move appears in Ezekiel 25:8 (Moab says Israel is &#8220;like all the nations&#8221; — which is both the insult and the accurate diagnosis). &#8220;They and their ancestors have transgressed against me right up to this day&#8221; establishes that the exile is not a surprising rupture but the climax of a continuous pattern — a theme developed extensively in ch. 20's historical review.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;Brazen-faced and stubborn-hearted&#8221; (<em>chazaqey-panim uqeshey-lev</em>) — the face-heart combination is physiognomic language common to wisdom literature: the face reveals the inner disposition, and a hardened face signals a hardened will. In ANE physiognomics (a developed discipline in Mesopotamia), facial features were correlated with character traits and destiny. Ezekiel uses this vocabulary to diagnose Israel's covenant condition: not merely behavioral disobedience but a structural orientation of will away from YHWH. The formula &#8220;Thus says the Lord GOD&#8221; (<em>ko amar Adonai YHWH</em>) appears over 200 times in Ezekiel — the royal messenger formula of the ancient Near Eastern diplomatic tradition, claiming the authority of the highest suzerain.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;Whether they listen or refuse — for they are a rebellious house — they will know that a prophet has been among them.&#8221; The prophetic commission is explicitly outcome-independent: success is not measured by audience response but by faithful delivery. This counters the common ancient assumption (and modern one) that a prophet's validity is proven by popular acceptance. The formula &#8220;rebellious house&#8221; (<em>beit hameri</em>) is Ezekiel's label for his audience throughout the book (2:5, 6, 7, 8; 3:9, 26, 27; 12:2, 3, 9, 25; 17:12; 24:3) — it frames every subsequent interaction as communication with a people whose disposition is already known to be hostile.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;Briers and thorns and scorpions&#8221; — the thorn-and-thistle imagery recalls the curse of Genesis 3:18 (the ground producing thorns after the fall) and is used elsewhere for hostile social environments (Mic 7:4; Isa 9:18). Scorpions represent lethal danger lurking in the territory one must traverse — a vivid image for the prophetic ministry among hostile hearers. The triple prohibition of fear (&#8220;do not be afraid... or be terrified... Do not fear... or be dismayed&#8221;) mirrors Joshua's commissioning formula (Josh 1:6-9) — Ezekiel is sent on a mission as difficult as entering Canaan, and requires the same divine assurance.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;You shall speak my words to them, whether they listen or not, for they are utterly rebellious&#8221; (<em>ki meri hemah</em>). The unconditional prophetic commission — speak regardless of response — is theologically important: it means Ezekiel's words are not conditional on audience readiness but on divine mandate. This principle is developed in ch. 3's watchman theology: the prophet's responsibility is discharge of the message, not guaranteeing its reception. The word &#8220;utterly rebellious&#8221; is the superlative of <em>meri</em> (rebellion), suggesting maximum resistance.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;Do not be like that rebellious house — open your mouth and eat what I give you.&#8221; The command to eat the scroll positions the prophetic word as food — a metaphor with deep roots in ANE royal-court tradition. Scribes who served the king literally &#8220;ate from the king's table,&#8221; and receiving the king's word was described in digestive terms. More directly, Jeremiah had said &#8220;your words were found and I ate them; your words became to me a joy and the delight of my heart&#8221; (Jer 15:16). Ezekiel is commanded to do literally what Jeremiah described metaphorically.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The hand extended with the scroll — a visual echo of hands that appear in prophetic visions (Isa 6:6-7, where a seraph takes a coal with tongs; Dan 10:18, where a hand touches Daniel). The scroll written on both sides (<em>panim veachor</em>) is unusual because ancient scrolls were typically written on one side only (the papyrus or parchment's smooth inner surface). Writing on the reverse (verso) was uncommon and associated with overflow — too much content for one side. The content — lamentations, mourning, woe (<em>qinah vahaggeh vahahi</em>) — covers the three Hebrew categories of grief literature.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The three words on the scroll — &#8220;lamentations, mourning, and woe&#8221; (<em>qinah vahaggeh vahahi</em>) — constitute Ezekiel's entire prophetic assignment in chs. 1-24: the announcement of judgment on Jerusalem and Judah. <em>Qinah</em> is the dirge-form of Hebrew poetry (typically 3+2 stress pattern, used in Lamentations); <em>haggeh</em> is groaning or moaning; <em>ahi</em> is the exclamation of distress. Together they are the sounds of a community in mourning — the sounds of 586 BCE being anticipated by the prophet in 593 BCE. The scroll pre-inscribes the future: the judgment is already written before Ezekiel speaks a word.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The command to eat the scroll precedes the commission to speak — the prophet must internalize the divine word before broadcasting it. This sequence is theologically significant: genuine prophetic speech is not a transmission of external information but an expression of inwardly digested truth. The same principle governs the Deuteronomic view of Torah (Deut 6:6: these words shall be on your heart) and the NT concept of the Spirit's indwelling enabling testimony.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;I opened my mouth, and he gave me the scroll to eat.&#8221; The divine initiative — YHWH gives, Ezekiel opens — maintains the asymmetry of prophetic commissioning: the prophet receives, he does not generate. The scroll is placed directly from YHWH's hand into the prophet's mouth, bypassing human agency. This parallels Isaiah's coal placed on his mouth by a seraph (Isa 6:6-7), and Jeremiah's commissioning where YHWH &#8220;touched his mouth&#8221; and said &#8220;I have put my words in your mouth&#8221; (Jer 1:9). The prophetic mouth is the location where divine word and human speech meet.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;Sweet as honey in my mouth&#8221; (<em>veyehi befiy kehoney lemathok</em>) — the sweetness of the scroll despite its terrible content (lamentations, mourning, woe) reflects the dual character of prophetic experience: the word of YHWH is both devastating in its content and delightful in its reception. The identical paradox appears in Revelation 10:9-10 (John instructed to eat a scroll: &#8220;sweet as honey in my mouth but bitter in my stomach&#8221;). Ps 19:10 had already established that the LORD's ordinances are &#8220;sweeter than honey.&#8221; The sweetness is not about the pleasantness of the message but about the intimacy of YHWH's word — to receive it is a gift even when its content is grief.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The commission to go to &#8220;the house of Israel&#8221; rather than to foreign nations establishes Ezekiel's primary audience as the exilic community at Tel-abib, not the Jerusalem population (who would have been addressed by Jeremiah). Ezekiel's prophetic geography is the Babylonian exile — he never returns to Judah and his oracles against Jerusalem are delivered from Babylon. This is itself a theological statement: YHWH's prophetic word is not confined to the land of Israel; the covenant relationship persists in exile.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;You are not being sent to a people of foreign speech and a difficult language&#8221; — the rhetorical contrast with foreign nations is sharp. Ezekiel is not sent to peoples who would have the excuse of linguistic incomprehension; he is sent to his own people who speak his language and know the covenant history. This makes their refusal to listen inexcusable rather than understandable. The foreign-nation contrast reflects a well-attested ANE motif: foreign peoples are sometimes depicted as more receptive to divine claims than Israel (cf. the sailors in Jonah 1; Nineveh in Jonah 3).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;If I had sent you to them, they would have listened&#8221; — the hypothetical receptiveness of nameless foreign peoples is YHWH's most damning indictment of Israel. This is the same logic Jesus uses in Matt 11:21-22 (Tyre and Sidon would have repented if they had seen the miracles done in Chorazin and Bethsaida). Covenant privilege creates covenant responsibility, and covenant breach by those with maximum privilege is maximum culpability. The foreigners are more open to YHWH than his own covenant people — a theme that runs from Rahab to Ruth to the Syrophoenician woman.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;All the house of Israel is hard-headed (<em>chashe-metzach</em>) and stubborn-hearted (<em>qeshe-lev</em>)&#8221; — the two-part diagnosis of Israel's resistance: the forehead (will-center) and the heart (thought/decision center) are both hardened. This is the theological root of the exile: not political or military inferiority but spiritual obstinacy. The same diagnosis underlies the new covenant promise of Ezek 36:26 (&#8220;I will remove the heart of stone and give them a heart of flesh&#8221;) — the solution to hard-heartedness is divine surgery, not human effort.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;I have made your face hard as their faces, your forehead hard as their foreheads&#8221; — YHWH's solution to prophetic intimidation is not to soften the audience but to harden the messenger. Ezekiel receives a divine hardening that matches and exceeds Israel's hardness — so that their stubbornness cannot overcome his. This is the prophetic version of the divine strengthening given to Moses (Exod 4:11-12), Joshua (Josh 1:6-9), and Isaiah (Isa 50:7: &#8220;I have set my face like flint&#8221; — the same <em>adamantine forehead</em> metaphor).</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>Shamir</em> (adamant) is a stone harder than flint — possibly corundum or emery, used for engraving harder stones. The metaphor reaches its maximum intensity here: harder than flint, set against Israel's forehead-resistance. The prophetic ministry is not a gentle pastoral conversation but a collision of wills in which YHWH has given his prophet material superiority. The prohibition of fear (&#8220;do not be afraid... or dismayed&#8221;) echoes the commissioning of Joshua almost verbatim (Josh 1:9) — prophetic courage is not natural bravery but divinely imparted fortitude.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Take all my words into your heart and hear them with your ears&#8221; — before Ezekiel speaks to Israel, he must fully receive the divine word himself. The sequence — receive → go → speak — mirrors the commission structure of Moses (Exod 4-6) and Isaiah (Isa 6). The double reception (heart and ears) ensures total internalization: not surface familiarity with the message but deep comprehension. This verse is the warrant for the preceding scroll-eating: the physical metaphor of eating corresponds to this spiritual reality of taking the word into the heart.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;Go to the exiles, to your own people&#8221; (<em>lach el-hagolah el-beney-amecha</em>) — Ezekiel's specific community is named: the <em>golah</em> (exile community), his own people. The word <em>golah</em> becomes a theological category in the exilic and post-exilic period (Ezra 1:11; 2:1; 4:1) — the exiles are not the remnant of a defeated nation but a preserved community with a future. Ezekiel's commission to the exiles presupposes their theological significance: YHWH is speaking to this community because this community has a future.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;Behind me I heard a great rumbling: 'Blessed be the glory of the LORD from his place!'&#8221; — this doxological exclamation is one of the most liturgically significant phrases in Ezekiel and became a central element of Jewish synagogue worship (it is recited in the Amidah prayer as &#8220;Baruch kevod YHWH mimqomo&#8221;). The phrase &#8220;from his place&#8221; (<em>mimqomo</em>) is theologically loaded: YHWH's place is not specified, because his glory is mobile (the entire point of the merkabah vision). The doxology is the heavenly court's response to the departing divine chariot — the living creatures' praise as the vision ends.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The sound of wings, wheels, and &#8220;a great roar&#8221; as the merkabah departs mirrors the arrival sounds of ch. 1. The repeated sound-description (wings + wheels) connects this departure to the earlier arrival, bracketing Ezekiel's commission with the same theophanic soundscape. Ancient temple worship in both Israel and Babylon involved elaborate soundscapes — choirs, instruments, processional music. The merkabah departs with the sound of the divine processional, claiming the same sonic grandeur as the Babylonian temple festivals that surrounded Ezekiel's community.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;I went in bitterness and grief of spirit&#8221; (<em>vaelech mar bamarat ruach</em>) — the prophet's emotional response to commissioning is not joy but bitterness. This is consistent with the content of his message (lamentations on the scroll) and with the pattern of reluctant prophets (Moses's resistance in Exod 3-4; Jeremiah's anguish throughout his confessions). Ezekiel does not embrace his prophetic role with enthusiasm; he goes because the hand of YHWH is upon him. The authenticity of prophetic reluctance is a feature, not a bug — it distinguishes genuine prophetic call from self-appointed proclamation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Tel-abib (Tel Aviv in modern Hebrew; the Israeli city takes its name from this location) was the central settlement of the Babylonian exile community, located near the River Chebar. &#8220;I sat where they sat&#8221; — the seven-day silent presence among the community mirrors Job's three friends who &#8220;sat with him on the ground seven days and seven nights, and no one spoke a word to him&#8221; (Job 2:13). Seven days is the standard mourning period in ancient Israelite practice (Gen 50:10; 1 Sam 31:13). Ezekiel's silence-as-solidarity establishes his identity with the community before he prophesies against them — he is one of them, not an outsider.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The seven-day waiting period before the word comes is a pattern in prophetic literature: Elijah waits at Horeb (1 Kings 19), Daniel mourns for three weeks before the vision comes (Dan 10:2-3). The waiting is not passive but preparatory — a period of absorption and orientation before active proclamation. The phrase &#8220;the word of the LORD came to me&#8221; (<em>vayehi devar-YHWH elai</em>) re-inaugurates the prophetic mandate after the silent solidarity period.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;I have made you a watchman for the house of Israel&#8221; (<em>tsopheh natatiykha leveit Yisrael</em>) — the watchman (<em>tsopheh</em>) was a defined role in ancient city defense: posted on walls or towers to observe approaching threats and give warning. 2 Sam 18:24-27 shows the watchman at the city gate reporting runners; Isa 21:6 receives a divine commission to set a watchman. Ezekiel receives a theological transformation of this civic role: not watching for military threats but for spiritual danger. The watchman's responsibility is defined in terms of blood-guilt — a covenant-legal category that makes the theological stakes explicit.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The first of the four watchman cases: warn not given to the wicked → prophet responsible for blood. The blood-guilt (<em>dam</em>) framework is grounded in Torah: Num 35:33 establishes that blood defiles the land, and the guilty party bears the blood-guilt (<em>naso dam</em>). Ezekiel 3:18-21 constitutes a formal four-case matrix (similar in structure to the casuistic law of the Covenant Code in Exodus 21-23) governing prophetic accountability. The key theological point is that the wicked person &#8220;will die for his sin&#8221; (<em>biavono yamut</em>) — death is the consequence of the person's own sin, not the prophet's silence; but the prophet who withheld warning is still liable.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The second case: warn given but not heeded → prophet not responsible. The prophet's discharge of responsibility is solely through the act of warning — the outcome (the wicked person's response) is beyond the prophet's control or responsibility. This is important for understanding Ezekiel's entire ministry: the repeated resistance of his audience does not invalidate his prophetic responsibility or indicate failure. The watchman who called out &#8220;the sword is coming&#8221; and was ignored has fulfilled his duty — the blood is on the hearer's hands.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The third case: righteous person who turns to sin, no warning given → prophet responsible. This is the most surprising case: even the righteous require watchman-care, because righteousness is not a permanent state immune to defection. &#8220;I place a stumbling block before them&#8221; (<em>venatatiy lifnav mikhshol</em>) — a theologically difficult phrase suggesting YHWH tests or allows testing of the righteous. The stumbling block (<em>mikhshol</em>) appears in Ezek 14:3-4 as an idol placed &#8220;before their face&#8221; — the lure of idolatry as the specific temptation of the righteous. &#8220;Their past righteousness will be forgotten&#8221; (<em>lo-tizakarna tsidqotav asher asa</em>) — there is no accumulated righteousness bank in Ezekiel's theology; relationship with YHWH is a present-tense reality, not a historical credit.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The fourth case: righteous person warned not to sin, heeds the warning → both prophet and righteous person &#8220;saved.&#8221; The use of &#8220;saved&#8221; (<em>natsalta et-naphsheykha</em>, you have saved your own life) for the prophet who faithfully warns is noteworthy: the prophet's own life is at stake in the discharge of the prophetic office. This is not about eternal salvation but about the covenant-legal standing that comes from faithful watchman-service. The entire four-case matrix is the formal theological framework for Ezekiel's entire prophetic ministry — revisited and expanded in ch. 33 when the watchman role is renewed after Jerusalem's fall.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The second encounter with the divine hand and the command to go to the valley (<em>habiqah</em>) marks a transition in the commission narrative. The <em>biqah</em> (valley or plain) is a specific geographic feature of Babylonian topography — the flat alluvial plain of Mesopotamia, as opposed to the hill country of Judah. The vision of divine glory in a Babylonian valley is a further assertion of YHWH's extra-territorial presence: the same glory that appeared by the Chebar canal (1:1) now appears in the open plain.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;The glory of the LORD was standing there, just like the glory I had seen by the River Chebar&#8221; — the verbal consistency (the same glory, the same description) confirms that Ezekiel is encountering the same divine presence. Multiple encounters with the divine glory are documented in the book (8:4; 10:18-19; 11:22-23; 43:2-5) — Ezekiel's prophetic vision is not a single revelatory event but an ongoing relationship with the mobile divine kavod. The prostration response (fell on my face) again signals the appropriate creaturely response to the divine presence.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Spirit entering, standing, and the command to go home and shut himself in (<em>lekh hisager betokh beyteykha</em>) — the commissioning moves from vision to practical instruction. The confinement to his house anticipates the sign-acts that follow in chs. 4-5, which are performed in domestic space rather than in public assembly. Ezekiel's prophetic ministry was largely enacted within the domestic space of the exile community rather than in public proclamation spaces — a contrast with the temple-court ministry of Isaiah and Jeremiah.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;Cords will be put on you, and you will be tied with them so you cannot go out among the people&#8221; — the cords are probably metaphorical (representing divine constraint on the prophet's freedom of movement) rather than literal (no one actually ties him up in the narrative). The same binding language describes the compulsion of prophetic calling elsewhere (Jer 20:9: &#8220;if I say I will not mention him... there is in my heart something like a burning fire shut up in my bones&#8221;). The prophet's freedom is circumscribed by the divine mandate — he goes where sent, says what commanded, acts as instructed.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;I will make your tongue stick to the roof of your mouth, and you will be silent&#8221; (<em>udveqah leshonkha el-chikkekha venilmata</em>) — the prophetic muteness that begins here continues until the fugitive arrives with news of Jerusalem's fall (24:27; 33:21-22). The muteness is not total (Ezekiel does speak throughout chs. 4-24) but selective and purposive — he speaks only the words YHWH gives him and is otherwise silent. This selective silence is a sign-act in itself: the prophet who cannot rebuke freely mirrors the community's situation under divine judgment, where normal covenant communication is suspended.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;When I speak to you, I will open your mouth&#8221; — the divine control of prophetic speech is explicit: YHWH opens and closes the prophetic mouth, not the prophet's own will. The closing formula &#8220;whoever listens, let him listen; and whoever refuses, let him refuse — for they are a rebellious house&#8221; (<em>hashomoah yishma vehechadal yechdal ki beit meri hemah</em>) is the ultimate expression of prophetic outcome-independence. Ezekiel's mission is outcome-independent: the commission is to speak faithfully, not to guarantee response. This principle governs his entire ministry of 22 years.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The clay tile (<em>levena</em>, literally a brick) for inscribing the siege of Jerusalem is a sign-act (<em>mofet</em>) — a performed symbolic action whose meaning YHWH specifies. City-model sieges were common in ANE military preparation: Assyrian records and reliefs depict siege-model exercises, and clay tablets from Mesopotamia show city plans used for military planning. Ezekiel uses the very medium of Babylonian administrative practice (clay tablets were the standard writing surface) to announce Jerusalem's fate. The sign is performed in the domestic space of the exile community — visible to those who visit his home.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The detailed siege vocabulary — wall (<em>dayeq</em>, siege-works), ramp (<em>solela</em>, earthen ramp for assault), camps (<em>machanim</em>, military encampments), battering rams (<em>karuyot</em>) — corresponds precisely to actual Babylonian siege techniques attested in Lachish reliefs and Assyrian military inscriptions. The Assyrian relief depicting the siege of Lachish (now in the British Museum) shows all these features: siege ramps, battering rams, military camps. Ezekiel's audience in Babylon would have been familiar with these siege methods — they had lived through one (597 BCE) and would recognize the signs.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The iron griddle (<em>machavet barzel</em>) placed between the prophet and the model city represents the iron wall of divine judgment between YHWH and Jerusalem. Iron was the strongest material available in the Iron Age — the griddle is an unbreakable barrier. The face-toward-the-city posture enacts prophetic opposition: the prophet's turned face signals YHWH's face turned in judgment. &#8220;This will be a sign to the house of Israel&#8221; (<em>vehaytah leot leveit Yisrael</em>) — the sign-act is explicitly labeled as communication, not mere dramatic performance.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The left-side position bearing the iniquity of Israel (northern kingdom) sets up the day-for-year scheme. &#8220;Bear iniquity&#8221; (<em>nasa avon</em>) is the priestly vocabulary for carrying guilt — used in Lev 16 for the scapegoat that bears Israel's sins. Ezekiel's body becomes a penitential instrument: he physically enacts the bearing of covenant guilt. The theological implication is significant: someone must carry the accumulated covenant-guilt of the people. In Ezekiel's sign-act, it is the prophet himself; the NT will identify the ultimate bearer as Christ (Isa 53:4, 11; 1 Pet 2:24).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The 390 days assigned to Israel's iniquity has generated extensive debate about its historical reference. Proposals include: years from the founding of the kingdom to the exile (roughly 390 years), years from the wilderness to the exile (Lev 26 promises 7×70 = 490 years of Sabbath-debts), or a schematic total for northern Israel's idolatry. The LXX reads 190 days rather than 390. Whatever the precise calculation, the <em>day-for-year</em> principle (<em>yom lashana yom lashana</em>, stated explicitly in v. 6) is the interpretive key — a large number of years is being compressed into prophetic days, making the weight of accumulated guilt tangible and visible.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Forty days for Judah's iniquity — forty is the covenant-discipline number in OT typology: forty days of flood (Gen 7:17), forty years of wilderness wandering (Deut 8:2), forty days of Moses on Sinai (Exod 24:18), forty days of Elijah's journey (1 Kings 19:8). The number forty in covenant contexts signals a complete period of testing or judgment leading to renewal. Judah's forty years represents the period of Babylonian exile — from 597/586 BCE to 538 BCE (Cyrus's decree) is approximately forty years, though Jeremiah's seventy years (Jer 25:11-12; 29:10) is the more common calculation. The forty-day sign-act compresses this discipline into visible form.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The bared arm (<em>zeruah chalufah</em>) is the combat stance of a warrior — baring the sword-arm removes the cloak to allow free movement. The same imagery appears in YHWH's &#8220;bared arm&#8221; as divine warrior in Isa 52:10 (&#8220;the LORD will bare his holy arm&#8221;). Ezekiel's prophetic posture enacts YHWH's own warrior-stance against Jerusalem — the prophet's body is a living theophany of the divine wrath.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The cords preventing Ezekiel from turning connect to the cords of 3:25 — the prophetic body is bound to the sign-act for its duration. The impossibility of turning from side to side mirrors Jerusalem's impossibility of escaping the siege: once YHWH's judgment begins, there is no turning. The 390+40 days total is a long prophetic performance — scholars debate whether this was literally maintained or was a symbolic instruction performed in abbreviated form.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The siege bread is a mix of cereals — wheat, barley, beans, lentils, millet, emmer (<em>kussemet</em>) — gathered into one vessel. Mixing grain types was normally prohibited (Lev 19:19; Deut 22:9) as a preservation of created order. The siege bread violates this by necessity: when food is scarce, purity regulations yield to survival. The bread is baked as small rounds (<em>ugot</em>) — the standard emergency bread of travel and scarcity (cf. the bread Elijah received from the angel in 1 Kings 19:6). The specific grain list corresponds to what would be available in a besieged city drawing on depleted stores.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Twenty shekels' weight per day (approximately 230 grams) is severe but survivable rationing — below normal caloric intake but not immediately life-threatening. &#8220;At set intervals&#8221; (<em>miet ad-et tochlennu</em>) emphasizes the controlled, measured nature of the distribution — no continuous access to food but scheduled allotments, which is the administrative practice of siege-food distribution. The scarcity is choreographed to be visible: those watching Ezekiel know exactly how little he eats each day.</p>",
    "11": "<p>One-sixth of a hin of water per day — a <em>hin</em> was approximately 3.5 liters; one-sixth would be about 580ml, barely enough for hydration. Ancient Near Eastern military sieges routinely weaponized water deprivation — cutting off access to water sources was a standard siege tactic. The measured water, like the measured bread, enacts the rationed desperation of a besieged city. The precision of the measurement (not &#8220;very little&#8221; but a specific fraction) is characteristic of priestly precision — Ezekiel the priest-prophet measures with priestly exactitude.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;Bake it over human excrement&#8221; — in the Torah, human excrement must be buried outside the camp (Deut 23:12-14) to maintain the holiness of YHWH's presence among the people. Using excrement as fuel violates this sanctity and renders the bread ritually defiled. The sign is about defilement in exile: when Jerusalem falls and the people are scattered among the nations, they will eat bread that cannot be ritually pure. The exile itself is a defilement event — Lev 18:24-28 had warned that the land would vomit out its inhabitants for covenant-violation, and the vomit of exile involves ritual impurity.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;This is how the Israelites will eat their defiled bread among the nations to which I drive them&#8221; — the interpretation of the sign connects the defiled bread directly to exile among the nations. The concern about eating defiled food in exile is attested in Second Temple Judaism: Daniel and his companions refuse the king's food (Dan 1:8-16), and Tobit is commended for not eating Gentile food (Tob 1:10-12). Ezekiel's sign-act anticipates the exile condition that later Jews navigated through purity rules and Torah-observance strategies.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ezekiel's protest — &#8220;I have never defiled myself&#8221; (<em>hineh naphshi lo metumah</em>) — is the priestly objection of a man whose life has been defined by Levitical purity. The three prohibitions cited (carrion, torn animals, unclean meat) are standard Levitical categories (Lev 11; 17:15; 22:8). His protest is not disobedience but legitimate priestly concern — the same concern that motivates Peter's refusal in Acts 10:14 (&#8220;I have never eaten anything common or unclean&#8221;). YHWH's accommodation in v. 15 shows that prophetic sign-acts have limits: the body of the prophet is not to be used without regard for the prophet's legitimate covenant commitments.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;Very well — I will allow you to use cattle dung instead of human dung&#8221; — YHWH's accommodation is an act of pastoral care for his prophet. Cattle dung was and is used as fuel in the ancient Near East (and still is in some regions) — it is a clean-burning material and its use does not carry the same defilement as human excrement. The accommodation preserves the sign (defilement of the bread, symbol of exile's ritual impurity) while respecting the prophet's priestly integrity. This divine responsiveness to the prophet's legitimate concern is itself a theological datum: YHWH is not a taskmaster who ignores the prophet's covenant commitments.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;I am about to break the food supply in Jerusalem&#8221; (<em>shover mateh-lechem birushalayim</em>) — &#8220;breaking the staff of bread&#8221; (<em>mateh lechem</em>) is a covenant-curse from Lev 26:26 (&#8220;when I break your supply of bread, ten women shall bake your bread in a single oven and shall dole out your bread again by weight, and you shall eat and not be satisfied&#8221;). Ezekiel's sign-act has been an enacted form of this specific covenant-curse: the rationed bread, the measured water, the defilement — all are fulfillments of Leviticus 26's covenant-curses for Israel's disobedience.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;They will lack bread and water, look at each other in horror, and waste away because of their iniquity&#8221; — the final verse of the bread-and-water sign connects the physical depletion to its theological cause: <em>avon</em> (iniquity/covenant-guilt). The sign-act is now complete and interpreted: every element (rationed bread, measured water, defiled baking, long duration) points to the siege-famine of 586 BCE and its cause in accumulated covenant-breach. Looking at each other in horror (<em>nashamu ish el-achiv</em>) is the social dissolution of community solidarity when resources are exhausted.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The barber's razor (<em>taar haggalabim</em>) applied to head and beard — shaving the head and beard was a sign of mourning and humiliation in the ancient Near East (Job 1:20; Jer 47:5; Isa 15:2). In Israel, shaving the head and beard was associated with mourning for the dead (Deut 14:1) and with the completion of a Nazirite vow (Num 6:18). The use of a sword (<em>cherev</em>) as a barber's razor is striking: the instrument of war performs the function of humiliation. YHWH weaponizes the mourning-rite into a prophetic action. The weighing and division of the hair on scales (<em>moznaim mishqal</em>) introduces the theme of measured judgment — precise, not random.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The three-part division of the hair enacts the three-thirds judgment of Ezek 5:12: a third burned in the city (plague and famine), a third struck with a sword around the city (war deaths), a third scattered to every wind (diaspora). This tripartite division of judgment has antecedents in ancient military practice — after the conquest of a city, prisoners were typically divided among captors (killed, enslaved, or resettled). YHWH applies the logic of conquest to his own city: Jerusalem will be treated as a conquered enemy city, because she has acted as one toward her covenant God.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;Take a small number of the hairs and tuck them into the folds of your cloak&#8221; — the small remnant in the hem of the cloak represents the tiny remnant that will survive the threefold judgment. The hem (<em>kanaf</em>) is also the part of the garment spread over a covenant partner (Ruth 3:9; Ezek 16:8) — the remnant preserved in the cloak's hem is under YHWH's protective cover. Even in the midst of the sign of total judgment, a remnant-sign is embedded: judgment does not equal annihilation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Even some of the hem-remnant will be thrown into fire — the remnant itself is not absolutely secure. This verse anticipates the theme of ongoing purification after the exile: not everyone who survives the Babylonian siege will be spiritually restored. Ezekiel's theology of the remnant is more rigorous than simple survivorship: the fire that comes from this remnant and spreads to the whole house of Israel points to the purifying-destructive quality of the divine presence (cf. Ezek 36:22-26, where restoration requires prior judgment).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;This is Jerusalem — I placed her in the center of the nations, with countries surrounding her on all sides&#8221; (<em>hibi Yerushalayim betokh hagoyim samtiyha usevivotyha aratsot</em>) — the cosmographic claim that Jerusalem is the center of the nations is well-attested in prophetic and wisdom literature (Ps 48:2; Ezek 38:12 uses <em>tabur haaretz</em>, navel of the earth). A Babylonian mappa mundi (world-map, ca. 6th century BCE, now in the British Museum) depicts Babylon at the center of a circular world surrounded by ocean — Ezekiel's claim for Jerusalem makes the same cosmographic assertion for YHWH's city that Babylon made for itself. The placement is divine act, not human achievement: &#8220;I placed her&#8221; (<em>samtiyha</em>).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;She has turned against my laws more than the nations&#8221; — the comparative judgment is devastating: Jerusalem, placed at the center with maximum revelation and covenant privilege, has been more disobedient than the pagan nations that surround her. The pagan nations have no Torah and no covenant, yet even they (by natural law or ancestral custom) maintain some moral order. Jerusalem, with the Torah, has &#8220;refused to walk in my statutes&#8221; more than those without them. The greater the privilege, the greater the culpability — a principle that runs from Amos 3:2 (&#8220;you only have I known of all the families of the earth; therefore I will punish you for all your iniquities&#8221;) through Matt 11:20-24.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The repeated &#8220;therefore&#8221; (<em>lachen</em>) structures the oracle as covenant lawsuit: accusation followed by verdict, evidence followed by sentence. Jerusalem has not merely failed to meet the standard of Torah; she has failed to meet even the lower standard of the surrounding nations' moral codes. This is the double indictment: rejection of the higher law (Torah) and failure even at the lower level (common moral order). ANE legal codes (Hammurabi, the Hittite Laws) provided a baseline moral standard that Israel's pagan neighbors maintained — Jerusalem fell below this baseline.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;I — yes, I myself — am against you&#8221; (<em>ani ani aleykhi</em>) — the emphatic first-person repetition is remarkable: YHWH is both the subject of the lawsuit (plaintiff) and the executioner. In ANE treaties, the suzerain could declare war on a vassal who violated the treaty — the covenant-curses of Leviticus 26 and Deuteronomy 28 are precisely this kind of suzerain-declaration. YHWH carrying out judgment &#8220;in the full sight of the nations&#8221; (<em>leeyney hagoyim</em>) has a paradoxical public dimension: the nations will witness YHWH judge his own people, which will both demonstrate his justice and complicate simple &#8220;YHWH is Israel's tribal god&#8221; interpretations.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;I will do to you what I have never done before, and what I will never do again, on account of all your abominations&#8221; — the unprecedented nature of the judgment is emphasized. The same language of unparalleled judgment appears in Dan 12:1 (&#8220;there shall be a time of trouble such as never has been since there was a nation&#8221;) and in Jesus's eschatological discourse (Mark 13:19: &#8220;there will be distress such as has not been from the beginning of the creation&#8221;). The fall of Jerusalem in 586 BCE was genuinely without precedent in Israel's history — the temple destroyed, the Davidic king deported, the promised land emptied.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Fathers will eat their sons within you, and sons will eat their fathers&#8221; — cannibalism during siege is a specific covenant-curse in Lev 26:29 and Deut 28:53-57. It is historically attested in the siege of Samaria (2 Kings 6:28-29) and the siege of Jerusalem in 70 CE (Josephus, War 6.3.3-4). The horror of the image in 5:10 is not merely rhetorical — it is the actual outcome documented in lamentations literature. Lam 2:20 and 4:10 confirm that women &#8220;cooked their own children as food&#8221; during the 586 siege. Ezekiel is not exaggerating for effect but citing the known covenant-curse trajectory.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;As I live&#8221; (<em>chi ani</em>) — the divine oath formula, which appears 16 times in Ezekiel (more than anywhere else in the OT). YHWH swears by his own life because there is nothing greater by which to swear (Heb 6:13: &#8220;since he had no one greater to swear by, he swore by himself&#8221;). The oath guarantees the irrevocability of the judgment: YHWH has committed his own existence to the outcome. &#8220;My eye will not spare and I will show no pity&#8221; (<em>lo-tachos eini velo echmol</em>) — the suspension of divine compassion is a deliberate covenant-curse enactment (Lev 26:28: &#8220;I will discipline you in fury&#8221;; Deut 28:50: &#8220;a nation of fierce countenance who shows no partiality&#8221;).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The three-thirds judgment (plague/famine, sword, scatter) maps the hair-division sign-act of vv. 1-4 onto historical outcomes. Plague and famine within the city = the siege conditions of 588-586 BCE; the sword around the city = the battle deaths when the walls were breached; scatter to every wind = the diaspora deportations. The precision of &#8220;drawing a sword in pursuit&#8221; (<em>cherev ariq achareyhem</em>) is covenant-curse language from Lev 26:33: &#8220;I will scatter you among the nations and will draw out a sword after you.&#8221; Ezekiel is announcing the execution of the specific penalties threatened in the covenant.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;Then my anger will be exhausted&#8221; (<em>venichal appi</em>) — the divine anger will be spent on Jerusalem rather than on the exilic community. The phrase &#8220;my fury will rest upon them and find its end&#8221; (<em>vanahachotiy chemati bahem venichamnti</em>) is paradoxical: YHWH &#8220;comforts himself&#8221; by spending his wrath on the judgment of Jerusalem. This is not divine sadism but covenant justice working itself out to completion — the wrath that must be paid accumulates until it is fully discharged. For the exile community hearing this, it carries the implication that once the judgment of Jerusalem is complete, YHWH's anger against the covenant community will be exhausted — opening the way for restoration (cf. Isa 40:1-2: &#8220;comfort, comfort my people... her warfare is ended, her iniquity is pardoned&#8221;).</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;I will make you a ruin and a disgrace among the surrounding nations, in the sight of all who pass by&#8221; — the public humiliation of Jerusalem before the nations is the reversal of Jerusalem's election-glory. In ANE royal ideology, a city's honor was its king's honor and its god's honor; a ruined city shamed its deity. YHWH accepts this shame on behalf of his covenant with the goal of ultimate vindication — a theme that Ezek 36:22-23 develops: YHWH acts to restore Israel &#8220;for the sake of my holy name.&#8221;</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;A disgrace and a mockery, a warning and a horror to the surrounding nations&#8221; — four terms of public humiliation (<em>cherpa vegerusha musar veshamah</em>). The word <em>musar</em> (warning/discipline) introduces a pedagogical dimension: Jerusalem's ruin will teach the nations something about YHWH's covenant-justice. This missionary-by-judgment theme is unexpected: Israel does not witness to the nations through blessing and prosperity in this passage, but through the spectacle of covenant-justice enacted upon herself. The nations learn about YHWH from his judgment of his own people — a pattern developed further in Paul's theology (Rom 11:11: Israel's transgression bringing &#8220;salvation to the Gentiles&#8221;).</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;The deadly arrows of famine&#8221; (<em>chitsam haraim haraav</em>, the evil arrows of famine) — famine is personified as divine weaponry in ANE battle-imagery. Deuteronomy 32:23 had described YHWH's arsenal: &#8220;I will heap disasters upon them; I will spend my arrows on them.&#8221; The intensification of famine (<em>vehosfati otah</em>, I will intensify it) and the cutting of the food supply (<em>shover mateh lechem</em>) complete the covenant-curse trajectory of Lev 26:26 enacted in ch. 4's sign-act. What was performed in miniature on the clay tile and with the rationed bread is now pronounced as historical reality.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The five instruments of judgment listed in the final verse — famine, ferocious beasts, pestilence, bloodshed, and the sword (<em>raav vachayah-raah vedesber vedam uverev</em>) — constitute the complete arsenal of divine judgment found in the covenant-curses. Lev 26:22 mentions wild beasts; Deut 28:21 mentions pestilence; Deut 28:25 mentions the sword. Ezekiel's five-instrument list is a comprehensive covenant-curse catalog. The closing formula &#8220;I, the LORD, have spoken&#8221; (<em>ani YHWH dibarti</em>) seals the oracle as irrevocable divine commitment — not a warning that can be averted but a declaration that has already been enacted in the heavenly council.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZEKIEL_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'ezekiel', existing)
    for ch in ['1', '2', '3', '4', '5']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with context commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
